What makes weather?
The sun.
Through the seasons, it heats our world; some parts more, some less. And, with the 
help of the Earth's rotation, this unequal heating becomes a giant engine that drives our 
weather
Anyone who has ever wilted outside on a sweltering summer day can figure out 
easily how the sun creates hot weather. But the connections are not so clear between the 
sun and hurricanes, or tornadoes, or blizzards, or the falling rain, or even long sieges of 
arctic cold.

How the sun creates energy
For centuries people thought of the sun as a giant object on fire, burning the way 
campfires burn. But imagine how much fuel you would need to keep that fire going. If 
something the size of the sun were made of gasoline and had enough oxygen to feed the 
flames it would burn about 10,000 years. That's a long time, but far short of the four and 
a half billion years the sun and Earth have existed.
Early this century, as we started learning more about radioactivity, scientists 
conjectured that somehow nuclear energy would explain the sun's power.
In 1938 Hans Bethe of Cornell University and Charles L. Critchaeld of George 
Washington University produced a theory explaining how nuclear fusion fuels the sun 
and other stars. A fusion reaction fuses atoms together creating other kinds of atoms and 
giving off energy. Fission reactions, like those used in today's nuclear power plants, split 
atoms to produce energy.

Besides the sun, the only source of heat on Earth is its molten core and radioactive 
rocks. While this heat supplies the energy to slowly push the continents around and 
build mountains, it hardly affects the weather. We encounter heat from deep below the 
Earth when geysers spew out water or when volcanoes erupt. And while a big volcano 
can darken the sky enough to affect the weather in some places, the impact is minor 
compared to the sun's daily work.

The sun's heat varies
Depending on the season and location, the sun bathes the Earth in widely varying 
amounts of energy. The result is a planet sharing frigid polar cold, sweltering tropical 
heat and all the temperatures in between - at the same time.
A heat engine depends on hot-cold contrasts to produce power. Your car is a good 
example. Power comes from the heat created by burning a mixture of gasoline and air in 
a cylinder. As the engine runs, its cylinders alternate between being hot and cooler. 
Power is produced.
Early in the 19th century, scientists discovered that the bigger the contrast between 
hot and cold in a heat engine, the more power it produces. That's why automotive 
researchers are looking for new materials that can withstand more heat than today's 
engine. An engine that could stand more heat would have bigger contrasts and produce 
the same power with less gasoline.
The atmosphere is similar. The stronger the hot-cold contrast, usually the stronger 
the storm.

Water holds the heat better
Land and water both absorb and give up heat. But land warms up and cools off more 
readily than water. Do your own science experiment. Go to the beach barefoot on a hot 
day at about 3 o'clock in the afternoon. The sand is almost too hot to walk on; the water is 
refreshingly cool. Now go back at midnight, especially on a clear night. The sand is chilly 
while the water has remained comfortably warm.
On a large scale, tropical oceans hold tremendous amounts of heat while polar water 
can be frigid year round. Land areas, on the other hand, quickly warm up or cool off with 
the seasons.

